\begin_layout Section
Question 1
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We consider three potential prior distributions, 
\begin_inset Formula $p(\theta)$
\end_inset

, of the probability that the Pistons win an NBA league basketball game.
 Games are either won or lost, no draws, and we model the win/lose variable
 as a binomial distribution, 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{i}\sim\mathcal{B}(1,\theta)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\theta\sim\mathcal{B}e(1,1)\label{eq:beta-1-1}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\theta\sim\mathcal{B}e(8,8)\label{eq:beta-8-8}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\theta\sim\mathcal{B}e(7,13)\label{eq:beta-7-13}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The mean, mode, variance, and 95% confidence intervals of these three distributi
ons are presented in the listing below.
