\begin_layout Standard
The 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{B}e(1,1)$
\end_inset

 distribution is the uniform distribution over 
\begin_inset Formula $[0,1]$
\end_inset

, and is least informative possible Beta prior.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{B}e(8,8)$
\end_inset

 has mean 
\begin_inset Formula $0.5$
\end_inset

 which mathes our external knowledge that win percentages are centred around
 50%.
 However, we also know that win percentages ranged from 20% to 70%, which
 constitutes evidence that distribution of win percentages is not balanced
 around 50%.
 The 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{B}e(8,8)$
\end_inset

 does not reflect this imbalance, but it is possible that the observed imbalance
 (
\begin_inset Formula $0.2$
\end_inset

 vs 
\begin_inset Formula $1-0.3$
\end_inset

) arose due to chance, so choosing a balanced prior 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{B}e(8,8)$
\end_inset

 is reasonable.
 The 95% confidence interval of the 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{B}e(8,8)$
\end_inset

 distributions aligns somewhat accurately with the stated knowledge that
 the range of actual observed win percentages (which equates roughly to
 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

, although the win percentages range over all teams, not just the Pistons)
 was between 20% and 70%, but hyperparameters could have been chosen to
 match this prior knowledge more accurately.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{B}e(7,13)$
\end_inset

 somewhat accurately expresses our belief that that the Pistons will win
 34% of games, 
\begin_inset Formula $7/(13+7)=0.35$
\end_inset

.
 However, this belief can be expressed with any of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{B}e(7k,13k)$
\end_inset

, where an increase in 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 represents an increase in our confidence in the Pistons winning 
\begin_inset Formula $35\%$
\end_inset

 of the games.
 The choice of 
\begin_inset Formula $k=1$
\end_inset

 reflects the fact the pundit seemed 'very confident'.
 However, there seems to be no reason why we didn't model the belief precisely
 as 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{B}e(\frac{28}{82}k,\frac{54}{82}k)$
\end_inset

, again with some choice of 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

, e.g.
 
\begin_inset Formula $k=20$
\end_inset

, to reflect the pundit being 'very confident'.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
So which of the 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{B}e(8,8)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{B}e(7,13)$
\end_inset

 distributions is a more informative prior? There are several metrics we
 can use to think about this question, and in all cases 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{B}e(7,13)$
\end_inset

 is the more 'informative' distribution, wholistically.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
1) The 95% confidence interval is narrower for 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{B}e(7,13)$
\end_inset

, i.e.
 range of values we have high confidence of observing is smaller, so we
 are expressing more certainty with 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{B}e(7,13)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
2) The variance is less for 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{B}e(7,13)$
\end_inset

.
 It is valid to compare the variances of the distributions because their
 PDFs both have the same domain.
 The lower variance again expresses greater certainty, i.e.
 more informativeness.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
3) We know that the probability of team 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 winning a game when 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 is unknown and we have no other information is 
\begin_inset Formula $0.5$
\end_inset

.
 The 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{B}e(7,13)$
\end_inset

 is opinionated about 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

 being less than 
\begin_inset Formula $0.5$
\end_inset

, whereas 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{B}e(8,8)$
\end_inset

 assigns equal probability to 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta<0.5$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta>0.5$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
3) The update rule for beta-binomial conjugate sets 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{\nu}:=a+\sum y_{i}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $b_{\nu}:=b+n-\sum y_{i}$
\end_inset

.
 The larger our value for 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

, the more dominating 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 is in the calculation of 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{n}$
\end_inset

, and similarly for 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $b_{n}$
\end_inset

.
 In this sense the 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{B}e(8,8)$
\end_inset

 has more influence on 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{n}$
\end_inset

 than does 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{B}e(7,13)$
\end_inset

, but 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{B}e(7,13)$
\end_inset

 has more influence on 
\begin_inset Formula $b_{n}$
\end_inset

 than does 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{B}e(8,8)$
\end_inset

.
 From this more nuanced perspective we can take either distribution to be
 more informative, depending on which hyperparameter we focus on.
 To tip the scales, however, the difference in influence on 
\begin_inset Formula $b_{n}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $13-8=5$
\end_inset

, is greater than the difference in influence on 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{n}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $8-7=1$
\end_inset

, and so wholistically 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{B}e(7,13)$
\end_inset

 is the more informative prior.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Question 2
